<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-065-072  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 065 072.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Jan 12 1989 n1146 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Food stores' number three checks it out. (computerized scanning inGateway Foodmarkets)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bicknell, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The United Kingdom's third largest food retailer, GatewayFoodmarkets, has begun using point-of-sale technology supplied byDatachecker, ICL and IBM in its stores.andP;  The benefits ofelectronic scanning include lowering a customer's time in thecheckout line, eliminating pricing irregularities, collectingsales data on individual items, and showing customers' buyinghabits.andP;  Gateway is now considering automatic labeling systems toelectronically produce shelf prices.andP;  Staff training is consideredanother important way to prevent errors.andP;  A national plan foron-site electronic funds transfer (EFT) has failed to emerge andGateway plans to introduce its own EFT plan in 1989.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Gateway Foods Inc. (automation).andO;Topic:     POS SystemsAutomationUnited KingdomFood Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>